  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **unlawful** in virtually every country around the world. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The process makes the funds appear to come from legitimate sources.\n\n**Why is it illegal?**  \nMoney laundering is a crime because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, tax evasion, and corruption by allowing perpetrators to use illicit funds without detection. It undermines the integrity of financial systems, fuels organized crime, and destabilizes economies.\n\n**Legal Consequences:**  \nLaws against money laundering are enforced globally, often with severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Many countries have established **anti-money laundering (AML)** regulations and require financial institutions to monitor and report suspicious transactions.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a **serious criminal offense** with significant legal and societal consequences.",
